\maketitle

\section*{Executive Summary}

India in 2025 is navigating a complex socio-political landscape marked by economic growth, communal polarization, and geopolitical tensions. The rise of Hindu nationalism, economic disparities, and historical legacies contribute to these dynamics, significantly impacting Generation Z (Gen Z). Many young Indians are drawn to Western countries for better education, jobs, and stability, facing cultural and racial challenges abroad. The Indian diaspora, a vital asset, contributes economically, politically, and culturally to India's development. Social work must adapt to support migrants, engage the diaspora, and address polarization through education, advocacy, and community programs.

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Complex Landscape}: Economic growth coexists with unemployment and polarization, driven by Hindu nationalism and historical factors.
    \item \textbf{Youth Impact}: Gen Z faces unemployment and mental health challenges, prompting migration aspirations.
    \item \textbf{Migration Drivers}: Education, economic opportunities, and stability attract youth to the West.
    \item \textbf{Diaspora Role}: The diaspora’s remittances and influence are crucial for India’s 2047 goals.
    \item \textbf{Social Work}: Must evolve to support migrants and foster inclusive policies.
    \item \textbf{Controversy}: Hindu nationalism and migration are sensitive, with diverse perspectives.
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Current Situation}

India’s socio-political environment is shaped by the Bharatiya Janata Party’s (BJP) Hindu nationalist policies since 2014, raising concerns about secularism. A 74.4\% increase in hate speech incidents from 2023 to 2024 highlights communal tensions. Economically, initiatives like “Make in India” drive growth, but youth unemployment (12.4\% in 2023) persists. Geopolitical tensions, such as the Kashmir conflict, add complexity.

\subsection*{Youth and Migration}

Gen Z, politically engaged yet disillusioned, faces economic and social pressures, driving many to seek opportunities in Western countries. Over 750,000 Indian students studied abroad in 2022, attracted by quality education and jobs. Migrants face cultural and racial challenges but contribute significantly to host economies.

\subsection*{Diaspora and Social Work}

The 35-million-strong diaspora sent \$120 billion in remittances in 2023, bolstering India’s economy. Social work must integrate migration studies, provide support services, and advocate for inclusive policies to address these challenges and leverage diaspora contributions.

\section*{Introduction}

As of May 2025, India stands at a crossroads, balancing rapid economic growth with persistent socio-political challenges. The country’s socio-political landscape is shaped by the dominance of Hindu nationalism, economic disparities, and geopolitical tensions, notably with Pakistan over Kashmir. These dynamics profoundly impact Indian youth, particularly Generation Z (Gen Z), who are navigating unemployment, communal polarization, and global aspirations. Many young Indians are drawn to Western countries for better education, economic opportunities, and socio-political stability, yet face cultural and racial challenges abroad. The Indian diaspora, estimated at 35 million, plays a critical role in India’s development through remittances, political influence, and cultural promotion. Social work, as a profession dedicated to social justice, must evolve to address these issues by supporting migrants, engaging the diaspora, and fostering inclusive policies. This report explores India’s current situation, its causes, its impact on youth, migration trends, diaspora contributions, and the role of social work in addressing these challenges.

\section*{Current Situation in India (2025)}

India in 2025 is characterized by a multifaceted socio-political and economic landscape:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Political Dynamics}: The BJP’s Hindu nationalist ideology, prominent since 2014, has led to policies criticized for undermining secularism. A 74.4\% increase in hate speech incidents from 2023 to 2024 (1,165 cases) reflects growing communal polarization, particularly affecting Muslims \citep{UserContext}.
    \item \textbf{Economic Progress and Challenges}: India is the world’s fastest-growing major economy, with 8.2\% GDP growth in FY23/24, driven by infrastructure investments (\href{https://santandertrade.com/en/portal/analyse-markets/india/economic-political-outline}{Santandertrade, 2024}). However, youth unemployment (12.4\% in 2023) and poverty persist \citep{UserContext}.
    \item \textbf{Geopolitical Tensions}: A terrorist attack in Kashmir on April 22, 2025, killed 26 people, escalating India-Pakistan tensions \citep{Wikipedia2025}. Both nations are preparing for potential conflict, with the EU urging restraint \citep{DW2025}.
    \item \textbf{Social Issues}: Public safety concerns, such as a crowd crush in Goa on May 3, 2025, highlight infrastructure challenges \citep{Wikipedia2025}.
\end{itemize}

